comment.narrative: Lower than 100% clearance rate for civil cases at first instance courts

New indicator added at restructuring in mid-2011. The MOJ is deciding on the coverage and training plan for court decisiondatabaseneeds and on the number of years of past court cases (2-5 years under consideration) to enter into the database.

title.narrative: Improved judicial training to raise level of professional performance

comment.narrative: Percent of judicial staff receiving systematic professional training
Percent of judicial staff receiving training according to new curricula

actual.value: Satisfactory progress is being made to improve judicial training and the Deputy Minister of Justice has also been appointed theDirector of the Judicial Academy reflecting increased importance given to improving judicial training.

comment.narrative: The MOJ has drafted the ToR for the curriculum development and upgrade for the Justice Academy (for judges, prosecutors, courtstaff and MOJ employees).2012 target: At least 80% of judicial and justice staff receive training
Following project restructuring, the end target is changed from "17 new courts constructed and 4 courts rehabilitated" to "11courtconstructed/rehabilitated"

actual.value: Oguz District Court completed Nov 2011. Yasamal, Gandja and Gedabek sites nearing completion. Shekhi and Sabunchu procurementsbegun.

title.narrative: Increased number of professional staff using IT based resource management system (RMS)

comment.narrative: An IT strategy and action plan for the justice sector was delivered to the MOJ; an automated case management system is underdevelopment; a document management system and an information network for pilot justice institutions and pilot courts is under way.

baseline.value: New law on registries passed but no locations automated

target.value: All urban regsitry locations and notary operations automated

actual.value: The E-Notary system is under development and will be completed by May, 2012.

baseline.value: No baseline survey on court user satisfaction conducted

target.value: At least 20% improvement in overall satisfaction with judicial services from overall baseline measure.

actual.value: The next user survey is not yet due.

title.narrative: Increased percentage of judges selected using new more objective selection procedures

baseline.value: No new judges selected using new procedures

target.value: At least 75% of new judges selected using new procedures

comment.narrative: Following restructuring and extension, the end target has been changed from "At least 150 new judges selected using newprocedures", which was met, to "At least 75% of new judges selected using new procedures"

actual.value: Selection of new judges is under way but end-project target already achieved.

comment.narrative: 78 candidates have cleared three stages of selection and are on the eve of appointment. When that happens, 92% of judges of firstinstance courts will have been selected according to the new competitive merit-based procedures.

title.narrative: Enhanced public access to legal and judicial information

baseline.value: No regional legal information centers or information available

target.value: At least 3 functioning regional legal information centers

comment.narrative: Legal Information Centers in Baku and Guba continue providing free legal aid in regions (2,600 users served).Informationbrochuresand other materials, production of TV reports and radio materials are being developed.

baseline.value: 90 days to enforce court decisions based on contract enforcement measurement in Doing Business

target.value: At least 20% reduction in time for court decision enforcement.

actual.value: Overall contract enforcement remains at 237 days (Doing Business 2011 Report)
